<h2>&#x1F4B0; Why Exchange Choice Matters During a Crash</h2>

<p>When BTC drops 50%, every basis point matters. Here&#x2019;s what to look for:</p>

<h3>1. Trading Fees</h3>
<p>A 0.5% difference on a $10,000 dip buy = $50. Over multiple buys during a crash, that adds up fast. Binance at 0.075% with BNB saves you 87% compared to Coinbase&#x2019;s standard 0.6%.</p>

<h3>2. Liquidity &amp; Slippage</h3>
<p>During crashes, order books thin. Binance and Coinbase have the deepest liquidity ” meaning your buy orders fill closer to the price you expect. Smaller exchanges can have 2-5% slippage during volatile moves.</p>

<h3>3. Withdrawal Speed &amp; Fees</h3>
<p>Once you&#x2019;ve bought, you may want to move to a hardware wallet (especially during exchange-failure panic). Binance and Coinbase offer free BTC withdrawals to external wallets, while some exchanges charge 0.0005 BTC ($32) per withdrawal.</p>

<h3>4. Security During Panic</h3>
<p>Not all exchanges handle crash traffic well. Coinbase has gone down during past volatility. Binance has the most battle-tested infrastructure. Always have a backup exchange account ready.</p>

<h2>&#x1F4E6; Step-by-Step: How to Buy the Bitcoin Dip in 2026</h2>

<h3>Step 1: Fund Your Account</h3>
<p>Before the next leg down hits, have funds ready. Deposit fiat via bank transfer (lowest fees), debit card (instant, higher fees), or USDT from another wallet.</p>

<h3>Step 2: Use Limit Orders, Not Market Orders</h3>
<p>Set limit orders at key support levels rather than buying at market. This protects you from slippage and lets you target specific prices. Most exchanges let you place limit orders for zero additional fees.</p>

<h3>Step 3: Dollar-Cost Average In</h3>
<p>Don&#x2019;t go all-in at one price. Split your buy across 3-5 price levels. Example: 20% at $64K, 30% at $60K, 30% at $56K, 20% at $50K. This protects against catching a falling knife.</p>

<h3>Step 4: Move to Cold Storage</h3>
<p>For significant holdings, move off exchange. A Ledger or Trezor hardware wallet protects against exchange insolvency risk (remember FTX?).</p>

